  "entries": {
    "turn-1-full": {
      "segments": [
        {
          "text": "We can use the present in Spanish to talk about the past, just as in English. For example: I ate, I was eating, and I have eaten. We'll focus on 'I have eaten', which uses 'haber'.",
          "lang": "en",
          "file": "turn-1-full-1.mp3",
          "hash": "4933c0c8cc95014ac319e2200ef86896054c75afcacff674fe569c6df54845b9"
        }
      ]
    },
    "turn-2-full": {
      "segments": [
        {
          "text": "The verb 'haber' is used for 'have' in 'I have eaten'. It's irregular, but we can remember its forms by focusing on its vowel sounds, /a/ and /e/. What are these vowel sounds?",
          "lang": "en",
          "file": "turn-2-full-1.mp3",
          "hash": "0a4e2cbc9325b2ee4339ae82647d36ca89f4c3bb6fc3544efdc4fbca9fb659bc"
        }
      ]
    },
    "turn-4-reveal": {
      "segments": [
        {
          "text": "Good. Let's start with 'he', which means 'I have'. It's spelled h-e. Now,",
          "lang": "en",
